42
00:02:42,800 --> 00:02:44,760
We revolve around it.

43
00:02:44,760 --> 00:02:48,880
So here is an earlier Ptolemaic conception of the universe.

44
00:02:48,880 --> 00:02:51,080
There in the center is the Earth.

45
00:02:51,080 --> 00:02:53,120
The Sun revolves around the Earth.

46
00:02:53,120 --> 00:02:59,040
And then other things revolve around the Earth as well, including the outer spheres containing

47
00:02:59,040 --> 00:03:00,920
the stars.

48
00:03:00,920 --> 00:03:05,240
Copernicus, on the other hand, said, no, no, it's not like that at all.

49
00:03:05,240 --> 00:03:07,600
In fact, the Sun is at the center of the solar system.

50
00:03:07,600 --> 00:03:10,960
The Earth and the other planets revolve around it.

51
00:03:11,960 --> 00:03:15,640
Well, Kant sees himself as doing something like that.

52
00:03:15,640 --> 00:03:17,320
Now exactly why?

53
00:03:17,320 --> 00:03:20,720
Why does he think he's transforming our perspective in this?

54
00:03:20,720 --> 00:03:27,480
Well, he sees himself as responding to the contrast between rationalism and empiricism,

55
00:03:27,480 --> 00:03:30,760
a contrast that dominated early modern philosophy.

56
00:03:30,760 --> 00:03:33,960
Kant himself was brought up in the rationalist tradition.

57
00:03:33,960 --> 00:03:37,760
He was a student of Christian Wolf, who was a student of Leibniz.

58
00:03:37,760 --> 00:03:40,880
And so he thought of things very much as Leibniz had.

59
00:03:40,880 --> 00:03:43,760
He sees himself as part of that rationalist tradition.

60
00:03:43,760 --> 00:03:50,080
However, he says that then he read David Hume, and Hume awoke him from his dogmatic slumber.

61
00:03:50,080 --> 00:03:54,720
At that point, he changed his perspective and realized that he had to do something to

62
00:03:54,720 --> 00:03:59,480
try to combine the insights of both the empiricist and the rationalist tradition.

63
00:03:59,480 --> 00:04:00,800
How did he do it?

64
00:04:00,800 --> 00:04:07,440
Well, the rationalists, people like Galvesena, Descartes, and Leibniz, had held that universality

65
00:04:07,440 --> 00:04:12,600
and necessity, the kind you find in scientific laws, for example, but also in mathematics,

66
00:04:12,600 --> 00:04:18,880
required synthetic a priori knowledge, knowledge of the world that was independent of experience.

67
00:04:18,880 --> 00:04:23,440
We weren't gaining a knowledge of universality from our particular experiences.

68
00:04:23,440 --> 00:04:27,160
We weren't gaining knowledge of necessity from our contingent experiences.

69
00:04:27,160 --> 00:04:31,600
Instead, they were being supplied from some other source, something that was not from

70
00:04:31,600 --> 00:04:36,080
experience at all, not a posteriori, so it had to be a priori.

71
00:04:36,080 --> 00:04:40,240
But it was really telling us something about the world, not just about language or concepts,

72
00:04:40,240 --> 00:04:42,760
and so it had to be synthetic as well.

73
00:04:42,760 --> 00:04:48,800
Well, Hume said, I think you've got the problem right, but the solution wrong.

74
00:04:48,800 --> 00:04:53,560
You're right that universality and necessity, causation, and a variety of other things aren't

75
00:04:53,560 --> 00:04:57,680
coming from your contingent and particular experiences of the world.

76
00:04:57,680 --> 00:05:01,080
However, they aren't coming from reason at all.

77
00:05:01,080 --> 00:05:06,040
There is no synthetic a priori savior waiting in the background to say, I have the cause

78
00:05:06,040 --> 00:05:09,920
and the concepts you need, I have the principles you need, I'm going to allow you to get to

79
00:05:09,920 --> 00:05:10,920
those conclusions.

80
00:05:10,920 --> 00:05:14,400
Instead, Hume says, look, here's what's going on.

81
00:05:14,400 --> 00:05:18,240
You see something happen a bunch of times, you get a feeling of expectation that it will

82
00:05:18,240 --> 00:05:19,240
happen again.

83
00:05:19,240 --> 00:05:21,720
It's that feeling, it's that sentiment inside you.

84
00:05:21,720 --> 00:05:23,240
It's not something rational.

85
00:05:23,240 --> 00:05:25,920
There is no bit of knowledge underlying it.

86
00:05:25,920 --> 00:05:28,080
Instead, it is simply a passion.

87
00:05:28,080 --> 00:05:33,120
It is custom or habit, but here, not a kind of cultural custom, instead a custom or habit

88
00:05:33,120 --> 00:05:34,120
of the mind.

89
00:05:34,120 --> 00:05:36,520
The mind does this, but why does it do it?

90
00:05:36,520 --> 00:05:38,520
Because it has this feeling inside.

91
00:05:38,520 --> 00:05:44,080
So it's all based on something internal, these internal impressions to use his language.

92
00:05:44,080 --> 00:05:48,100
Kant says, I think Hume is right that the source is in us.

93
00:05:48,100 --> 00:05:51,000
But he's wrong to say it's something outside of reason.

94
00:05:51,000 --> 00:05:53,880
It's just a feeling, it's just sentiment.

95
00:05:53,880 --> 00:05:56,960
Kant says instead, no, it is something inside us.

96
00:05:56,960 --> 00:05:58,600
In that respect, he's right.

97
00:05:58,600 --> 00:06:01,200
But it's really part of reason itself.

98
00:06:01,200 --> 00:06:04,520
So in that sense, he remains in the rationalist tradition.

99
00:06:04,520 --> 00:06:11,560
He says Descartes, Leibniz, other rationalists basically had it right, in that there are

100
00:06:11,560 --> 00:06:18,800
synthetic a priori bits of knowledge that supply the gaps here that take us from contingent

101
00:06:18,800 --> 00:06:23,240
particular experience to universal and necessary conclusions.

102
00:06:23,240 --> 00:06:27,160
But it's not as if they are things that are sort of automatic.

103
00:06:27,160 --> 00:06:32,120
And once we realize their character, we realize they're very limited in what they can do

104
00:06:32,120 --> 00:06:38,160
for us, they can apply to the appearances, the things we actually perceive in experience,

105
00:06:38,160 --> 00:06:39,960
but they have no further application.

106
00:06:39,960 --> 00:06:43,280
Well, how does he get there?

107
00:06:43,280 --> 00:06:48,680
Here's the question Kant asks, and it's a disturbing but very fundamental question.

108
00:06:48,680 --> 00:06:55,600
Do our concepts revolve around objects, as realists, for example, think, or do the objects

109
00:06:55,600 --> 00:06:58,280
revolve around our concepts?

110
00:06:58,280 --> 00:07:01,520
We've talked about the possible gap between mind and world.

111
00:07:01,520 --> 00:07:08,200
And now we can say, well, you might think the problem is that the world is what it is,

112
00:07:08,200 --> 00:07:11,520
and mind has the job of conforming itself to the world.

113
00:07:11,520 --> 00:07:13,040
Kant says, what if it's the reverse?

114
00:07:13,040 --> 00:07:18,000
What if the mind is what it is, and the world has to conform to it?

115
00:07:18,000 --> 00:07:19,560
That's his revolution.

116
00:07:19,560 --> 00:07:25,120
There isn't that serious a gap between mind and world, not because mind is adapted to

117
00:07:25,120 --> 00:07:31,040
understanding the world, but because the world is adapted to being understood by mind.

118
00:07:31,040 --> 00:07:32,440
Here's how he puts it.

119
00:07:32,440 --> 00:07:37,760
It is hitherto been assumed that our knowledge must conform to the objects, but all attempts

120
00:07:37,760 --> 00:07:42,080
to ascertain anything about these objects a priori by means of concepts, and thus to

121
00:07:42,080 --> 00:07:47,080
extend the range of our knowledge, have been rendered abortive by this assumption.

122
00:07:47,080 --> 00:07:51,280
Let us then make the experiment whether we may not be more successful in metaphysics

123
00:07:51,320 --> 00:07:55,720
if we assume that the objects must conform to our knowledge.

124
00:07:55,720 --> 00:07:58,480
Well, that is his remarkable revolution.

125
00:07:58,480 --> 00:08:03,000
He says, the problem isn't getting our ideas to conform to the objects in the world.

126
00:08:03,000 --> 00:08:06,480
Instead, it's the objects problem to conform to our mind.

127
00:08:06,480 --> 00:08:09,000
Now, that's a bit surprising, right?

128
00:08:09,000 --> 00:08:13,040
I mean, you might think, look, it's my job to investigate, to find out about the world.

129
00:08:13,040 --> 00:08:14,240
Kant says, relax.

130
00:08:14,240 --> 00:08:17,600
It's the world's job to conform itself to you.

131
00:08:17,600 --> 00:08:20,400
Now, at first glance, that seems bizarre.

132
00:08:20,400 --> 00:08:22,720
You might say, no, I don't think it's really like that.

133
00:08:22,720 --> 00:08:24,280
It's a little harder than that, right?

134
00:08:24,280 --> 00:08:28,600
Why would I have to go to school if it's the world's job to conform itself to my mind?

135
00:08:28,600 --> 00:08:30,200
It looks like I don't have to learn anything.

136
00:08:30,200 --> 00:08:32,040
I don't have to exert any effort.

137
00:08:32,040 --> 00:08:35,400
It's the world's job to match me.

138
00:08:35,400 --> 00:08:37,600
But of course, that's not quite what he means.

139
00:08:37,600 --> 00:08:45,440
What he means is that our minds are constituted in such a way that they can only process the

140
00:08:45,480 --> 00:08:51,800
information that our bodies and our minds are receiving from the world in certain ways.

141
00:08:51,800 --> 00:08:56,880
And they form out of that information they're receiving, a conception of objects.

142
00:08:56,880 --> 00:09:01,560
Those objects, as we understand them, are constructed by the mind.

143
00:09:01,560 --> 00:09:02,880
He was right about that.

144
00:09:02,880 --> 00:09:05,960
Objects are being constructed by us.

145
00:09:05,960 --> 00:09:10,560
But he's saying to that extent, the objects have to conform to the mind because the mind

146
00:09:10,560 --> 00:09:12,200
is building them.

147
00:09:12,200 --> 00:09:14,280
But the world is giving us this information.

148
00:09:14,320 --> 00:09:16,000
It's not as if that's a bizarre idea.

149
00:09:16,000 --> 00:09:20,000
No, the world is somehow transmitting information to us.

150
00:09:20,000 --> 00:09:22,920
But then we are processing that information.

151
00:09:22,920 --> 00:09:28,760
And what we do with it forces it to conform to the structures of our mind.

152
00:09:28,760 --> 00:09:33,480
So the objects, as we understand them, are part of the output of that process.

153
00:09:33,480 --> 00:09:35,440
So of course, they conform to the mind.

154
00:09:35,440 --> 00:09:38,120
It's not the mind's job to conform to those objects.

155
00:09:38,120 --> 00:09:42,320
Those objects are constructed in such a way that they do conform to the basic structures

156
00:09:42,320 --> 00:09:43,680
of my mind.

157
00:09:43,680 --> 00:09:49,120
That's how it's possible for me to know something a priori about them.

158
00:09:49,120 --> 00:09:53,080
Let's take a look at how Caught compares himself to Copernicus.

